\begin_layout Standard
Three days later, Zorian was kind of regretting one-upping Zach like he did.
 Ever since then, his fellow time traveler seemed obsessed with duplicating
 Zorian's feat, refusing to understand that this wasn't something you could
 achieve by working on it really hard for a couple of days.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I'm not even sure why you're so upset about this," Zorian finally told him.
 "It's just a neat trick that people like you have no need for anyway."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"It's the principle of the thing," Zach said, casting another magic missile at
 the tree in front of him.
 Zorian didn't think the poor plant would last long if this continued for long.
 "I'm the combat guy.
 It's my thing, and I've been at this for decades longer than you! I can't let
 you outdo me in this area."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zorian sighed at the explanation.
 He was getting uncomfortable flashbacks to Taiven's little episode when she
 figured out how good of a combat mage he is.
 Was this a general combat mage thing?

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well, at least Zach was not crying over it like Taiven had… that would have
 been 

\emph on

really

\emph default

 awkward.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"At least let me show you how to do it properly," Zorian said.
 "You'll never succeed by going at it in your current fashion."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach stopped for a second, considering it, before shaking his head.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Maybe if I still can't figure it out in a few days," he said.
 "I like to figure these sorts of things on my own."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Oh well, he tried.
 With a helpless shrug, Zorian left Zach to his pointless attempts at
 brute-forcing a problem that required finesse to solve.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Eventually Zach either ran out of mana or got sick of casting magic missile –
 probably just got sick of it, considering his monstrous mana reserves – and
 decided to sit down next to Zorian for a while.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Do you mind if I ask you a little about what you remember about the start of
 the time loop?" Zorian asked after a while.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Feel free," Zach shrugged.
 "But keep in mind that the beginning of the time loop is very fuzzy in my mind
 and I keep having trouble remembering specific things about it."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yeah, you mentioned that," Zorian nodded.
 "But I've been thinking about what you've said, both recently and back when
 you still thought I was unaware of the time loop…"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"That was an asshole thing for you to do," said Zach, interrupting him.
 "I know I've said it before, but it bears repeating."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You're never going to shut up about it, are you?" Zorian complained.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Nope," Zach confirmed.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Anyway," Zorian said, deciding there was no point in continuing that topic, "I
 remember you mentioning how you kept trying to convince everyone who would
 listen about the existence of the time loop.
 What was your logic behind that?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I found myself in some crazy time loop and there was an invasion of the city
 at the end of every month," Zach said.
 "Of course I wanted some help."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"So just to confirm…" Zorian tried.
 "Your earliest memories are of being confused by the situation you found
 yourself in, yes? The time loop was strange and novel to you, not something
 that felt natural?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach frowned, lost in thought for a while.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yeah," Zach nodded.
 "Sounds about right.
 It doesn't feel like the time loop was something I was informed of in advance
 or specifically groomed for, if that's what you're asking.
 I guess that's a point in favor of Red Robe being the true Controller, huh?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Him being the original Controller still makes no sense to me," Zorian said.
 "Why would he tolerate you all this time if you weren't somehow critical for
 the loop? Do you remember ever experiencing a time loop being cut short for no
 apparent reason?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"No," Zach said.
 "I would have remembered something that abnormal.
 I did experience a few unexpected restarts while sleeping, but I'm pretty sure
 those were due to assassinations."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Hmm.
 I doubt Red Robe never died prematurely, so that means the time loop 

\emph on

only

\emph default

 resets when you die.
 That's a pretty obvious indicator it considers you more important than the two
 of us."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They continued discussing the issue for another ten minutes of so, with no
 solid conclusions by the end.
 Eventually they shifted to the topic of how to convince people around them
 they really were in a time loop and Zach started sharing some of his more
 amusing failures in his initial quest for allies…

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You told Benisek that you're a time traveler?" Zorian asked incredulously.
 "I can't believe you thought it was a good idea."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Shut up," Zach said.
 "Aren't you friends with the guy?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Eh, sort of," Zorian admitted.
 "But I'm afraid our friendship didn't quite survive the time loop and its
 influence on me.
 I kind of feel bad, since it's not his fault he can't learn and grow like I
 do, but…"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"You don't have to explain that to me," Zach said.
 "I used to be casual friends with a lot of our classmates, but I feel
 completely alienated from most of them by now."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Right," said Zorian.
 Best not to dwell on such a depressing topic.
 "So what exactly happened when you told Benisek about the time loop?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I thought he took it quite well at first," Zach said.
 "Then I came to school the day after and found that he told half the school
 I've gone completely nuts.
 Though funnily, everyone seemed to have a different idea of what kind of crazy
 thing I believed in…"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Yeah, that sounds like Benisek," Zorian nodded.
 "So when you said you tried to convince everyone, you really meant everyone,
 huh?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Well, obviously I couldn't try to convince literally everyone in Cyoria," Zach
 said.
 "But it was a lot of people.
 Students, teachers, city authorities, you name it."

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zorian tapped his fingers against the ground around him, trying to think of
 some person from their class whose reaction to the time loop would have been
 amusing.
 Oh!

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"How about Veyers?" he asked Zach.
 "Did you ever tell him about the time loop?"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Who?" Zach asked, looking confused.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Veyers Boranova," Zorian said.
 "You know, the guy who punched you in the face during class in our second
 year? He got expelled from the academy before the time loop began, but he had
 technically been our classmate, so I thought…"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
He stopped when he noticed Zach was giving him a strange look.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"What is it?" he asked.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"Zorian… who the hell are you talking about?" Zach asked him slowly.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zorian stared at Zach for a while, before he began to explain things in more
 detail.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I'm talking about Veyers Boranova," he said.
 "Member of Noble House Boranova and our classmate during the first two years
 of our education.
 Tall, blond, and with vivid orange eyes that had a slitted iris and made him
 look sort of like a snake.
 You two hated each other… well, just about everyone hated the asshole, and he
 seemed to hate everyone around him, so I guess that doesn't say much but…
 Anyway, the point is that there is no way you could have forgotten the guy!"

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Zach shifted in place uncomfortably.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
"I have no idea who you're talking about," he finally admitted.

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wow.
 Now that… that was very, 

\emph on

very

\emph default

 interesting.

\end_layout



